As an introverted, self-employed creative person who values privacy, running a business shouldn't feel so awkward, but sometimes it really does. Most online resources and mentors tell you to interact with large (evil) tech companies in an extroverted way. Here, you should advertise, follow the algorithms, share your personal charm. Get verified on that platform, stay online 24/7, answer questions with your own videos, and respond immediately. Videos, videos, and more videos.
1/3
For me, this year is a year of transformation.
I no longer want to dedicate my money, data, and energy to large technology companies, nor do I want to listen to mentors who only push a single, outward-facing solution onto everyone. I am exploring new business models and also striving to overcome my long-held belief that success can only be achieved by following a specific way of doing things.
Wish me luck!
The first step has already been taken.
I have left Facebook, removed all Meta and Pinterest trackers from my website, and logged out of my personal WhatsApp account.
Yesterday, I also removed the last external tracker from my website - Google Analytics, and it felt great.
To better support GDPR, I recently subscribed to a European CRM service and plan to migrate my business over the next few weeks.
I transferred my MX records to Proton, now I have full SPF, DKIM, and DMARC set up without needing to pay Google for basic email verification.
3/3
